   {:e #blake3 "521f084a789746410383eec40ee3061f6ca5918411eb0b1aeda43c08fec2ac86" :a :task/description :v "COMPREHENSIVE VERIFICATION for DAEMON-SCALE. SEVEN TEST CATEGORIES: === CAT 1: SEMANTIC EQUIVALENCE (INV-DAEMON-004) === Run each of 11 routable commands via WAL-backed daemon AND via direct mode on identical store. Compare output and store state. All must match. === CAT 2: WRITE THROUGHPUT (50 AGENTS) === Fork 50 processes, each sends 10 writes. All 500 complete in < 30s. All 500 datom sets in store. fsync count < 200 (group commit working). Zero stale cache reads. === CAT 3: READ CONCURRENCY === Fork 20 processes sending status simultaneously while 10 processes write. All 30 complete. Read results consistent. Wall time < 2× single-read time (proving read concurrency). === CAT 4: DURABILITY === Write 100 txns. SIGKILL daemon at random point. Restart. Count recovered txns >= txns that received DurabilityPermit (CLI got response). Count lost txns = txns in flight at kill time (no CLI response — expected loss). Run 20 iterations to cover different kill points. === CAT 5: GIT READINESS === Write 100 txns to daemon. Run braid harvest --commit (triggers FULL checkpoint). git status .braid/txns/ shows exactly 100 new .edn files. git add + git commit succeeds. Clone to separate directory. braid status on clone shows all 100 txns. === CAT 6: THREE-LEVEL RECOVERY === (a) Fast: checkpoint + WAL delta. (b) Medium: corrupt WAL, recover from checkpoint + edn delta. (c) Slow: corrupt checkpoint, recover from edn-only. All three produce identical Store state. === CAT 7: REGRESSION === cargo test — all existing tests pass. braid status shows correct metrics. Performance: braid observe < 5ms through daemon. braid status < 100ms through daemon (warm). === E2E SCRIPT === scripts/e2e_daemon_scale.sh (~500 lines). Each test: isolated tempdir, daemon start, operations, assertions with detailed logging (daemon PID, WAL size, checkpoint LSN, .edn count, datom count, timing). On failure: full diagnostic dump." :op :assert}
